Passing northwards, they emerged from the deep, and took up their abode in the savage wilds of Seangleann, on the south-west of Donegal. Here they re- mained unmolested till our Tirconnellian saint was directed by an angel 10 rid the place of its soul inhabitants. After a violent struggle with the demens, he completely routed them, and with the help of the Dubh-duaibseacla his bell, drove them once for all into the sea. His name was henceforward associated with the tract, and the wild par-ish of Gleneolumbkill preserves in its topography and traditions a living commentary on the legend of St. Co— lumba‘s first visit to it, as told by Manus O’Don- nell in 1510. (vit. S. Columbae, i. 89, Tr. Th. p. 403 b.) Sliabh Liag, commonly called Slieve- League, a precipitous mountain in this region, commands, in clear weather, a view of Croagh Patrick on the south-west.
